Slide 7 — The Internet Has the Same Problem

The Internet assumes:

Fast responses (TCP handshake: SYN, SYN-ACK, ACK)
Continuous connections
Stable routes

Space provides:

Long delays
Intermittent links
Orbital motion

Slide 8 — Why TCP Breaks in Space

Show a TCP handshake over a lunar link:

SYN → (1.3 seconds) → arrives at Moon
SYN-ACK → (1.3 seconds) → arrives back at Earth
ACK → (1.3 seconds) → arrives at Moon

3.9 seconds just to say hello. Before any data moves.

Now try Mars: 3–22 minutes each way.

A TCP handshake to Mars could take over an hour.

Slide 9 — Distances That Break Your Brain

Destination         One-way Delay
London–New York     ~30 ms
GEO Satellite       ~120 ms
Moon                ~1.3 s
Mars                3–22 min
Jupiter             35–50 min

What does a Zoom call to Mars look like?

You say hello.
You wait 22 minutes.
They say hello back.
You wait another 22 minutes to hear it.

Slide 10 — "But What About Starlink?"

Someone's thinking it.

Starlink is LEO. It's Earth infrastructure.

It doesn't solve the physics of cislunar or interplanetary distances.

Even if you put Starlink around the Moon, you still have 1.3-second delays, orbital occlusion, and no continuous path to Mars.

The problem isn't bandwidth. It's the speed of light.

