Slide 12 — A Solar System Postal Service

Introduce:

Delay-Tolerant Networking (DTN)

Simple explanation:

Store
Carry
Forward
Deliver

No continuous connection required.

A bundle (like a parcel) is handed off node to node until it reaches its destination. If the next hop isn't available, the node holds onto it.

When a bundle is "in flight" for 22 minutes to Mars — the sending node is responsible for it until the next node confirms receipt.

Slide 13 — Routing by Time

Visual:

Earth visible to relay 12:00–12:10
Relay visible to Moon 12:30–12:40

In space, you often know future connectivity in advance.

You know the satellite will be visible at 14:32 tomorrow.

So you schedule the transmission now.

This is Contact Graph Routing — the network equivalent of a train timetable.

For anyone who's only worked with IP routing, this is genuinely alien.

