Speaker Notes

Pacing: 22 slides for 40 minutes = ~1.8 minutes per slide. Comfortable pace with room for pauses and audience reactions.

The balance should be approximately:

15% space context (slides 2–4)
15% personal credibility and motivation (slides 5–6)
30% the networking problem and DTN concepts (slides 7–13)
10% professional context / not science fiction (slide 14)
20% RADIANT and amateur radio (slides 15–20)
10% close and call to action (slides 21–22)

Key principles for EMF:

- The audience leaves talking about "building infrastructure beyond Earth", not about protocol stacks.
- Use analogies they know: UUCP, postal service, train timetables.
- Pre-empt the Starlink question — it shows you've thought about it.
- The TCP handshake example makes the problem visceral for anyone who's written networked code.
- The demo (even pre-recorded) makes RADIANT tangible.
- End on the emotional line (slide 21), keep the logistics (slide 22) as a backdrop for Q&A.
- Cross-reference the AMSAT Village session to funnel interested technical people.
- QR code on the final slide — people will photograph it.
